    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-19T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-19T11:00:00-05:00" n="1273"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1273">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860H.01/870: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bucknell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-19T18:00:00+02:00"
                            >May 19, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 19—5:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4046. King Peter yesterday dismissed the Puric government. Foreign Office says
                    that it has very little information as to the personalities who may be included
                    in the new Yugoslav Government, but it is quite certain that the Ban of Croatia
                    will play a prominent part, in its formation. It is probable that he will be
                    Prime Minister. Mihailovic definitely will not be included in the new
                    government. The Foreign Office says this will be very small in number and that
                    it will represent a break with the former associations, although it may be
                    necessary to take in one or two of the older politicians as there is <pb
                        facs="1384" n="1374" xml:id="pg_1374"/> nobody else available. The Foreign
                    Office believes that a conciliatory gesture will be made to Tito. All is in the
                    hands of King Peter, on whom the final decisions rest.</p>
                <p>The Embassy will report further developments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bucknell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
